This paper deals with variational approximation methods in Bayesian inference, which is a common topic in machine learning and statistics. The use of manifold parameterization and Riemannian stochastic gradient descent method suggests a focus on optimization techniques, which is often studied in the subfield of machine learning (cs.LG). The application of these techniques to high-dimensional problems also suggests a potential connection to computer vision (cs.CV) and natural language processing (cs.NA). Additionally, the use of factor covariance structure and Gaussian approximation suggests a potential connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and statistical theory (cs.ST).
